subsection.p:
Now let's compute the slopes of the two lines in Example 1.  Choose two points on the graph of y=2,  say (-5,2) and (4,2).  Use these points to compute the slope.

        \begin{aligned}
                m \amp = \dfrac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} = \dfrac{2-2}{4-(-5)}\\
                  \amp = \dfrac{0}{9}=0  
                \end{aligned}

The slope of the horizontal line y=2 is zero.  In fact, the slope of any horizontal line is zero, because the y-coordinates of all the points on the line are equal.  Thus
        m = \dfrac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} = \dfrac{0}{x_2-x_1}=0

On a vertical line, the x-coordinates of all the points are equal. For example, two points on the line x=-3 are (-3,1) and (-3,6).  Using these points to compute the slope, we find

        \begin{aligned}
                m \amp = \dfrac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1} = \dfrac{6-1}{-3-(-3)}\\
                  \amp = \dfrac{5}{0}  
                \end{aligned}

which is undefined. The slope of any vertical line is undefined because the expression x_2-x_1 equals zero.

solution.p:
The lines are parallel if their slopes are equal. We can find the slope of the first line by putting its equation into slope-intercept form. We solve for y:
\begin{aligned} 3x+6y \amp = 6 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Subtract 3x from both sides.}}\\ 6y \amp = -3x+6 \amp\amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by 6.}}\\ y \amp = \dfrac{-3x}{6}+\dfrac{6}{6} \amp\amp \blert{\text{Simplify.}}\\ y \amp = \dfrac{-1}{2}x+1 \end{aligned}
The slope of the first line is m_1=\dfrac{-1}{2}. The equation of the second line is already in slope-intercept form, and its slope is m_2=\dfrac{-1}{2}. Thus, m_1=m_2, so the lines are parallel.

sidebyside.p:
\begin{aligned}
                y \amp = \dfrac{2}{3} x-2\\
                y \amp = \dfrac{-3}{2} x+3  
                \end{aligned}      
shown at right. The lines appear to be perpendicular. The relationship between the slopes of perpendicular lines is not as easy to see as the relationship for parallel lines. However, for this example, m_1=\dfrac{2}{3} and m_2=\dfrac{-3}{2}.

subsection.p:
Note that 
m_2=\dfrac{-3}{2}=\dfrac{-1}{\dfrac{2}{3}}=\dfrac{-1}{m_1}

This relationship holds for any two perpendicular lines with slopes m_1 and m_2, as long as m_1\not=0 and m_2\not=0.

\begin{aligned}
                4x-2y \amp = 6  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Subtract 4x from both sides.}}\\
                    -2y \amp = -4x+6  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by -2.}}\\ 
                    y \amp = \dfrac{-4x}{-2}+\dfrac{6}{-2}  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Simplify.}}\\
                    y \amp = 2x-3
                \end{aligned}

The slope of the given line is ~m_1=2.  Because the unknown line is parallel to this line, its slope is also 2.  Now we know the slope of the desired line, ~m=2,  and one point on the line, (1,4). Substituting these values into the point-slope formula will give us the equation.

    \begin{aligned}
                y-y_1 \amp = m(x-x_1)\\
                y-\alert{4} \amp = \alert{2}(x-\alert{1})  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Apply the distributive law.}}\\ 
                y-4 \amp = 2x-2  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Add 4 to both sides.}}\\
                    y \amp = 2x-2
                \end{aligned}

solution.p:
Now we use the point-slope formula with m_1=\dfrac{-1}{2} and (x_1,y_1)=(1,4).
    \begin{aligned}
                y-y_1 \amp = m(x-x_1)\\
                y-4 \amp = \dfrac{-1}{2}(x-1)  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Apply the distributive law.}}\\ 
                y-4 \amp = \dfrac{-1}{2}x+\dfrac{1}{2}  \amp\amp \blert{\text{Add 4 to both sides.}}\\
                    y \amp = \dfrac{-1}{2}x+\dfrac{9}{2}  \amp\amp \blert{\dfrac{1}{2}+4=\dfrac{1}{2}+\dfrac{8}{2}=\dfrac{9}{2}}
                \end{aligned}
